content.text:
The issue was that `SpacingBetweenDeclarationsWithAnnotationsRule` incorrectly identified the "start" of a declaration when it was preceded by KDocs (specifically double KDocs or potentially even complex single KDocs). The helper function `getPrevLeafIgnoringCommentAndWhitespaceExceptBlankLines` iterates backwards over leaf elements. However, KDocs are composite PSI elements (`KDoc`), and their children (tokens) do not implement `PsiComment` individually. The original code only checked `psiElement is PsiComment`, so when it encountered a KDoc token (like `KDOC_END` or `KDOC_TEXT`), it treated it as a non-comment, non-whitespace element, causing the traversal to stop prematurely.

This premature stop caused the rule to think the declaration "started" right after the KDoc (i.e., at the newline before the annotation), which typically has a newline count of 1. Consequently, the rule concluded that there was no blank line before the declaration, even if there was one before the KDoc, leading to a false positive violation.

I fixed this by adding a check `isPartOfComment()` which traverses up the PSI tree to determine if a leaf element is part of a `PsiComment` (like `KDoc`). This ensures that KDoc tokens are correctly skipped as comments.

Reference to the fix implementation:
`ktlint-ruleset-standard/src/main/kotlin/com/pinterest/ktlint/ruleset/standard/rules/SpacingBetweenDeclarationsWithAnnotationsRule.kt`

